{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15ce4514-e0f8-4c19-8b35-23a292ea6467","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org.\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool=true` | Marks the package as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum configuration. Want me to scaffold this into your actual project file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61c30e52-ae16-4a3c-8657-ebd6d0f989da","outputTokens":514,"requestId":"B025:360FF2:DCAC3A:F9BF80:6A027E34"},"id":"275b09a4-e72b-4630-b183-9e0dc8ee6801","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:11:25.119Z","parentId":"44ed2092-b1d1-4bd1-a4f0-3053e508deb9"}
